<div class="indented"><a id="comment-5468"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/scatter-bluetooth-keyboards-everywhere#comment-5468" class="active">I&#039;m holding off</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Tue, 2008-06-10 13:40.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>The new intel Atom, including the supposed dual-core one, looks like it should break this market wide open.  The MSI Wind looks much better for the price than the ASUS.</p>

<p>Ideally you want a processor that can go really low-power for ordinary stuff, but has the ability to peak to do fancy things like videoconferencing, or playing HDTV.</p>

<p>If we got these keyboards everywhere, and we got hotels providing computer inputs on the flat panel HDTVs they are all installing, then my choice might move to something even smaller.   The smaller it is, the more you will have it with you, but the less often you will accept it as all you need &#8212; unless you can readily dock it all over the place and get stuff done that needs a screen, mouse and keyboard.</p>

<p>I think we&#8217;ll see a lot of movement here.  On the other hand, EEEPCs and the Wind are cheap enough you won&#8217;t go bad buying one and getting something better in a year.</p>
</div>
